    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1967-05-31T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1967-05-31T00:00:00-05:00" n="113"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d113">
                <head>113. Memorandum From the President’s Special Assistant (<persName
                        corresp="#p_RWW1" type="from">Rostow</persName>) to President <persName
                        corresp="#p_JLB1" type="to">Johnson</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d113fn1">Source: <persName corresp="#p_JLB1"
                            >Johnson</persName> Library, National Security File, Country File,
                        Middle East Crisis, Vol. III. Confidential. A handwritten “<gloss
                            target="#t_L1">L</gloss>” on the memorandum indicates the President saw
                        it.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1967-05-31">May 31, 1967</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Today’s Security Council Meeting</item>
                </list>
                <p>We presented our interim resolution-calling for Security Council endorsement of
                        <persName corresp="#p_TU1">Thant</persName>’s appeal to forego belligerence
                    and for further diplomatic and <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> efforts to
                    resolve the crisis.<note n="2" xml:id="d113fn2">
                        <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> document S/7919.</note> In his speech,
                    Justice Goldbe<gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> called on the members of the
                    Security Council to have the <pb facs="0240" n="208" xml:id="pg_208"/> courage
                    to exercise their responsibilities and to harmonize their actions to save the
                    world from the scourge of war.</p>
                <p>The <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss> subsequently presented a resolution
                    essentially calling for a reversion to the situation before 1956.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d113fn3">
                        <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> document S/7919.</note> The <gloss
                        target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss> Representative attacked the 1951 Security
                    Council Resolution (which said that neither side was entitled to belligerent
                    rights). His basis was that some of the states voting for the resolution should
                    have abstained as parties to the dispute and that the resolution was based on
                    the “permanent character” of the Armistice which had been shattered by the 1956
                    attack.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_FNT1">Fedorenko</persName> maintained a running, sarcastic
                    challenge to <persName corresp="#p_GAJ1">Goldberg</persName> to explain our
                    naval blockade of Cuba in 1962 in light of our present championing of maritime
                    rights.</p>
                <p>Various Arab countries continued their attacks on Israel. Japan supported
                        <persName corresp="#p_TU1">Thant</persName>; India supported the <gloss
                        target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss> Resolution; Ethiopia made a temporizing
                    down-the-middle statement; and France called for-and got-an adjournment until
                    10:30 a.m. Friday<note n="4" xml:id="d113fn4">June 2.</note> in order to study
                    both resolutions (and, obviously, to get further instructions).</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWW1">Walt</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
